02:01:34.787 --> 02:01:35.818
<i>But his lap times are slower now...</i>

02:01:35.842 --> 02:01:38.018
- His lap times are awfully erratic, Jeff.
- Yeah.

02:01:38.190 --> 02:01:41.091
<i>...on the BRM. They're Barlini, number 18,</i>
<i>who was just ahead...</i>

02:01:41.260 --> 02:01:45.162
<i>of number 17, Jean-Pierre Sarti,</i>
<i>14, Pete Aron, and 11, Jochen Rindt.</i>

02:01:45.331 --> 02:01:48.789
<i>These three are having a great dice</i>
<i>for third place.</i>

02:02:09.288 --> 02:02:11.318
<i>At Bottom Bend,</i>
<i>Stoddard lost three more places.</i>

02:02:11.491 --> 02:02:13.686
If he keeps missing shifts like that,
the car will level last.

02:02:13.860 --> 02:02:17.393
It'll last longer than he will.
He's finished already.

02:02:17.563 --> 02:02:20.760
<i>Barlini's the leader,</i>
<i>but he's not far ahead of Sarti and Aron.</i>

02:02:22.635 --> 02:02:25.103
<i>Here's Stoddard coming into the pits</i>
<i>very slowly.</i>

02:02:25.271 --> 02:02:27.671
<i>My goodness, he looks as if</i>
<i>he's on the edge of collapse.</i>

02:02:27.840 --> 02:02:31.207
<i>What a shame,</i>
<i>he was driving a beautiful race.</i>

02:02:35.815 --> 02:02:38.181
<i>Scott Stoddard</i>
<i>does seem to be in a bad way.</i>

02:02:38.551 --> 02:02:41.912
<i>His retirement certainly puts</i>
<i>a new complexion on the race.</i>

02:02:42.288 --> 02:02:44.982
<i>Barlini leads, but Ferrari team leader</i>
<i>Sarti, Aron...</i>

02:02:45.158 --> 02:02:47.456
<i>and Rindt, all have</i>
<i>the Sicilian in their sights.</i>

02:02:47.627 --> 02:02:50.489
<i>There's a tremendous battle for second place</i>
<i>between Sarti and Aron.</i>

02:02:50.663 --> 02:02:54.155
<i>Although there's one more World</i>
<i>Championship race to go at Monza in Italy...</i>

02:02:54.333 --> 02:02:58.667
<i>the result here at Brands Hatch</i>
<i>is very important to both these men.</i>

02:02:58.838 --> 02:03:02.239
<i>Izo Yamura himself is dedicated to winning</i>
<i>the Constructors Championship...</i>

02:03:02.408 --> 02:03:04.638
<i>and Aron is his only hope</i>
<i>here at Brands.</i>

02:03:04.810 --> 02:03:08.576
<i>His second car, driven by Tim Randolph,</i>
<i>blew up its engine early in the race.</i>

02:03:22.828 --> 02:03:24.796
<i>Here comes the leader, Barlini.</i>

02:03:26.632 --> 02:03:29.829
<i>He's not far ahead</i>
<i>of Sarti, Aron and Rindt.</i>

02:03:31.672 --> 02:03:35.004
<i>Last lap. Only one lap to go.</i>
<i>Sarti and Aron are very close to Barlini now.</i>

02:03:35.174 --> 02:03:36.903
- The last lap.
<i>- But Aron hasn't a chance...</i>

02:03:37.076 --> 02:03:40.045
<i>of getting past both Ferraris. This is</i>
<i>going to be the most exciting finish...</i>

02:03:40.213 --> 02:03:42.272
<i>of the Grand Prix season so far.</i>

02:03:53.058 --> 02:03:56.994
<i>At Bottom Bend, the first four</i>
<i>are nose-to-tail: Barlini, Sarti, Aron, Rindt.</i>

02:04:00.032 --> 02:04:01.829
<i>Barlini dare not let Sarti through.</i>

02:04:02.001 --> 02:04:04.401
<i>It's much too dodgy</i>
<i>with the Yamura right behind.</i>

02:04:05.071 --> 02:04:08.529
Look. He's spilling something.
Looks like fuel.

02:04:08.707 --> 02:04:09.935
Gas leaking?

02:04:34.733 --> 02:04:37.133
<i>As they come into Clearways,</i>
<i>Barlini's still in front.</i>

02:04:37.303 --> 02:04:39.271
<i>The Yamura's smoking badly. It's on fire.</i>

02:04:39.438 --> 02:04:40.837
He's on fire!

02:04:41.006 --> 02:04:43.839
<i>The Yamura's second,</i>
<i>ahead of Sarti's Ferrari. It's on fire.</i>

02:04:44.009 --> 02:04:46.978
<i>It's well and truly on fire.</i>
<i>But Aron's not slowing.</i>

02:04:47.146 --> 02:04:51.139
<i>He's gonna beat Sarti to the finish.</i>
<i>There's the flag, Barlini wins for Ferrari.</i>

02:04:51.317 --> 02:04:53.551
<i>Aron's second and Sarti third.</i>

02:04:53.719 --> 02:04:55.443
<i>Now, the Yamura's</i>
<i>pulling off the track.</i>

02:04:55.621 --> 02:04:59.284
<i>There are flames shooting out of the back</i>
<i>of the car. Let's hope Aron can get out.</i>

02:04:59.458 --> 02:05:01.949
<i>There's a fire crew right there.</i>
<i>He should be all right.</i>

02:05:02.128 --> 02:05:04.762
<i>He's rolled out of the car.</i>
<i>Keep back. Keep back.</i>

02:05:04.930 --> 02:05:08.864
<i>What a shambles. Some of the crowd</i>
<i>are rushing to the fire, and Sarti's stopping.</i>

02:05:09.035 --> 02:05:11.396
<i>He's going to see</i>
<i>if there's anything he can do for Aron.</i>

02:05:11.570 --> 02:05:14.630
<i>Izo Yamura's also running</i>
<i>across the track with Tim Randolph.</i>

02:05:14.807 --> 02:05:17.207
<i>From here, it looks</i>
<i>as though Pete Aron's on his feet.</i>

02:05:17.376 --> 02:05:19.241
<i>- He must be okay but I tell you...</i>
- Are you all right?

02:05:19.411 --> 02:05:21.538
- I'm okay.
<i>- ...for the last few seconds of the race.</i>

02:05:21.714 --> 02:05:23.182
I'm okay. I'm okay.

02:05:23.849 --> 02:05:25.942
- Are you all right?
- Yeah, what'd we make?

02:05:26.118 --> 02:05:28.245
- Second.
- I'm a regular ball of fire.

02:05:28.420 --> 02:05:31.189
<i>A fire like this is what these drivers</i>
<i>are most afraid of.</i>

02:05:31.357 --> 02:05:34.651
<i>Nowadays their fireproof no make overalls</i>
<i>give them a good deal of protection.</i>

02:05:34.827 --> 02:05:36.954
- Get out of here!
<i>- Photographers must keep back.</i>

02:05:37.129 --> 02:05:38.960
<i>Please keep back.</i>

02:05:46.205 --> 02:05:50.266
<i>Nino Barlini's up there on the trailer</i>
<i>ready to go around on his lap of honor.</i>

02:05:50.442 --> 02:05:53.536
<i>The team manager of Ferrari is there too.</i>

02:05:54.813 --> 02:05:59.477
<i>And there's a beautiful bird coming up</i>
<i>to join him on the trailer up there.</i>

02:06:01.620 --> 02:06:03.212
Hey, Nino.

02:06:03.389 --> 02:06:05.914
Nino Barlini, excuse me. Congratulations.

02:06:06.091 --> 02:06:08.218
- How do you feel after that splendid victory?
- Thank you.

02:06:08.394 --> 02:06:12.763
My neck hurts, my leg.
My hand is bleeding. And I feel wonderful.

02:06:12.932 --> 02:06:15.423
Well, I don't know
if you've had time to realize it...

02:06:15.601 --> 02:06:18.764
but this means that you're one point
ahead of Sarti and Stoddard...

02:06:18.938 --> 02:06:22.203
- ...two points ahead of Pete Aron.
- Of course I realize it.

02:06:22.374 --> 02:06:24.774
And with one race to go at Monza...

02:06:24.944 --> 02:06:27.879
the man who wins at Monza
will be the world champion.

02:06:28.047 --> 02:06:29.674
I am the man.

02:06:29.848 --> 02:06:33.340
So long, Nino. Congratulations.

02:06:35.221 --> 02:06:38.054
I feel wonderful.

02:07:09.455 --> 02:07:10.854
Yeah, come in.

02:07:23.168 --> 02:07:24.396
How are you?

02:07:31.210 --> 02:07:33.542
I'm pretty bloody awful.

02:07:34.046 --> 02:07:35.707
How are you?

02:07:53.132 --> 02:07:54.895
Would you...

02:07:55.067 --> 02:07:56.432
care to sit down?

02:08:03.809 --> 02:08:06.073
This has been a ridiculous few weeks,
hasn't it?

02:08:07.479 --> 02:08:08.605
Has it?

02:08:10.582 --> 02:08:14.143
Well, I mean, seeing each other
at the races and not...

02:08:15.788 --> 02:08:17.221
Well, ignoring each other.

02:08:18.791 --> 02:08:20.486
Trying to.

02:08:25.898 --> 02:08:28.594
I've been alone.

02:08:29.268 --> 02:08:31.429
You know that, don't you?

02:08:32.671 --> 02:08:34.901
Yeah. Here.

02:08:36.542 --> 02:08:40.308
- Pete said you had guts, and I...
- I'm not really interested in what he said.

02:08:41.113 --> 02:08:43.877
I certainly don't want to discuss him
with you. I've told you that.

02:08:44.049 --> 02:08:45.607
I didn't mean...

02:08:46.885 --> 02:08:50.412
I meant that when he said you had guts,
I said you were only stubborn.

02:08:50.589 --> 02:08:54.218
I just wanted to tell you
that he was right and I was wrong.

02:08:55.661 --> 02:08:58.630
Watching what you've been doing
these past few weeks...

02:09:00.199 --> 02:09:02.429
You shouldn't have been doing it alone.

02:09:02.968 --> 02:09:05.334
Yeah, there's only room for one
in the car, you know.

02:09:05.604 --> 02:09:08.732
- I don't mean that. You know I don't.
- I know.

02:09:09.675 --> 02:09:11.438
It was a joke.

02:09:12.878 --> 02:09:14.971
Do you still want me, Scott?

02:09:20.119 --> 02:09:21.643
Yes.

02:09:23.722 --> 02:09:26.691
I still feel the same
about what you're doing.

02:09:26.859 --> 02:09:29.350
That hasn't changed, you know.

02:09:29.528 --> 02:09:30.825
I think you're a fool.

02:09:31.964 --> 02:09:33.898
Yeah, I know.

02:09:36.201 --> 02:09:38.032
But...

02:09:39.938 --> 02:09:42.566
I haven't changed either, you know.

02:09:43.909 --> 02:09:45.467
I mean...

02:09:49.248 --> 02:09:51.716
I really can't promise you anything.

02:09:51.884 --> 02:09:53.818
That's all right.

02:09:54.820 --> 02:09:58.278
That's the problem, really.
People promise each other too much.

02:11:04.957 --> 02:11:07.187
What's wrong, Jean-Pierre?

02:11:08.861 --> 02:11:10.556
What is it?

02:11:13.131 --> 02:11:16.760
There's nothing you can do
about what's wrong with me, Louise.

02:11:16.969 --> 02:11:20.132
I won't admit that
until I know what's troubling you.

02:11:21.440 --> 02:11:24.967
I suppose what's wrong with me
is my life.

02:11:25.210 --> 02:11:28.976
But I can't change it. Or won't.

02:11:30.282 --> 02:11:33.115
So there's nothing you can do for me.

02:11:34.653 --> 02:11:36.883
What's wrong with your life?

02:11:37.823 --> 02:11:41.384
I've begun to see the absurdity of it.

02:11:42.294 --> 02:11:44.194
All of us.

02:11:46.465 --> 02:11:48.456
Proving what?

02:11:49.101 --> 02:11:50.864
That we can go faster?

02:11:51.036 --> 02:11:53.561
And perhaps remain alive?

02:11:55.474 --> 02:11:58.671
Nino, gambling his life for a trophy...

02:11:58.844 --> 02:12:01.438
then fills it with beer and does tricks.

02:12:01.847 --> 02:12:05.044
Stoddard, filling himself with drugs
in order to drive...

02:12:05.217 --> 02:12:07.242
and still passing out with the pain.

02:12:07.419 --> 02:12:10.513
Don't you see how absurd it all is?
Who cares?

02:12:11.924 --> 02:12:13.858
I thought you cared.

02:12:14.059 --> 02:12:16.084
For yourselves.

02:12:17.229 --> 02:12:20.062
I didn't know you asked it
of anyone else.

02:12:20.799 --> 02:12:22.926
Nevertheless, others do care.

02:12:23.101 --> 02:12:24.898
A hundred thousand
of them cared today.

02:12:25.070 --> 02:12:28.506
And did you see them rush
to see Peter burn?

02:12:28.674 --> 02:12:33.043
Did you see the looks
on their faces? I saw.

02:12:33.211 --> 02:12:36.874
For the first time today,
I really saw those faces.

02:12:37.049 --> 02:12:38.607
But not all of them, Jean-Pierre.

02:12:38.784 --> 02:12:43.244
There are some who come for that,
for the accidents and the fires.

02:12:44.957 --> 02:12:49.587
But the others,
the others ride with you, maybe.

02:12:50.495 --> 02:12:55.296
You put something in their lives
that they can't put there themselves.

02:12:57.169 --> 02:12:58.602
Are you one of those?

02:13:03.475 --> 02:13:04.737
It doesn't matter.

02:13:07.546 --> 02:13:09.036
Yes, it does.

02:13:09.848 --> 02:13:12.373
Maybe I am one of those.

02:13:13.485 --> 02:13:16.784
When I came here three months ago...

02:13:16.955 --> 02:13:22.757
there was a place in my life
that needed to be filled.

02:13:23.595 --> 02:13:24.584
You've done that.

02:13:26.665 --> 02:13:30.567
You and, I suppose,
the excitement of what you do.

02:13:31.703 --> 02:13:33.500
But you offered me these things, Jean-Pierre.

02:13:33.672 --> 02:13:37.073
You can't condemn me now
for having accepted them.

02:13:37.376 --> 02:13:40.937
No, I don't condemn you
for that, darling.

02:13:41.647 --> 02:13:43.205
Sorry.

02:13:48.954 --> 02:13:51.218
Jean-Pierre, you can stop.

02:13:52.424 --> 02:13:57.088
If you feel as you do,
you could stop now.

02:13:59.498 --> 02:14:03.958
No, it's not so easy.

02:14:06.004 --> 02:14:07.699
Not so easy.

02:14:10.742 --> 02:14:13.210
Not so easy.

02:14:17.382 --> 02:14:19.543
<i>With the Italian Grand Prix</i>
<i>at the Monza Autodrome...</i>

02:14:19.718 --> 02:14:22.983
<i>they're using a combination</i>
<i>of the banked oval high-speed track...</i>

02:14:23.155 --> 02:14:24.713
<i>and the road circuit.</i>

02:14:24.890 --> 02:14:27.222
<i>The whole thing comes</i>
<i>to almost six and a quarter miles...</i>

02:14:27.392 --> 02:14:30.259
<i>just over half of this length</i>
<i>being the road circuit...</i>

02:14:30.429 --> 02:14:32.897
<i>with its fast corners</i>
<i>and long straights.</i>

02:14:33.065 --> 02:14:35.693
<i>By itself, it's one of the</i>
<i>fastest circuits in the world.</i>

02:14:35.867 --> 02:14:40.065
<i>And combined with the oval track,</i>
<i>it should give some phenomenal speeds.</i>

02:14:57.656 --> 02:15:00.386
Why hasn't my car arrived, Guido?

02:15:00.559 --> 02:15:03.289
It's no longer in my hands,
Jean-Pierre.

02:15:33.925 --> 02:15:35.358
What's the trouble?

02:15:35.527 --> 02:15:38.963
My car hasn't arrived
from the factory.

02:15:39.564 --> 02:15:41.532
The same thing
has happened before.

02:15:41.700 --> 02:15:45.864
Not to me, but to other drivers
who have fallen from grace.

02:15:46.071 --> 02:15:47.368
Pressure.

02:15:47.539 --> 02:15:48.972
Pressure?

02:15:49.141 --> 02:15:51.735
Isn't there enough of that as it is?

02:15:52.177 --> 02:15:56.113
You have to grasp the mind
of Signor Manetta, my darling.

02:15:56.381 --> 02:15:58.542
If a driver can be reached
by those tactics...

02:15:58.717 --> 02:16:01.982
it means he probably will fear
for his place on the team.

02:16:02.154 --> 02:16:04.554
That is exactly
what Manetta wants.

02:16:04.723 --> 02:16:08.352
Because that driver will try
all the harder to win.

02:16:08.527 --> 02:16:12.930
He will perhaps take a risk
which he would ordinarily avoid.

02:16:13.098 --> 02:16:17.467
And risks are always risks.

02:16:19.171 --> 02:16:21.264
But the car will come.

02:16:21.439 --> 02:16:24.931
Well, if it doesn't,
I'll use my influence...

02:16:25.110 --> 02:16:28.273
and I'll get you the best seat
in the grandstand.

02:16:36.555 --> 02:16:40.218
- No sign of it?
- No.

02:16:40.392 --> 02:16:43.555
Don't worry, Jean-Pierre.
That's what they want you to do.

02:16:44.830 --> 02:16:46.627
He makes a great mistake, then.

02:16:59.611 --> 02:17:02.409
Are you sure
you wanted it to come?

02:17:10.388 --> 02:17:14.950
<i>A maximum of about 180 miles an hour</i>
<i>can be expected from these 3-liter cars...</i>

02:17:15.126 --> 02:17:17.719
<i>on this high banking,</i>
<i>where they get...</i>

02:17:18.063 --> 02:17:22.727
<i>a tremendous pounding from the rough surface and</i>
<i>the strain imposed by centrifugal force...</i>

02:17:22.901 --> 02:17:25.392
<i>before they swoop down</i>
<i>onto the road circuit again...</i>

02:17:25.570 --> 02:17:28.800
<i>where cornering power</i>
<i>handling are at the premium.</i>

02:17:42.254 --> 02:17:46.156
- Good afternoon, Nino.
- Madame Sarti.

02:18:08.046 --> 02:18:10.981
Have you met Miss Frederickson?
Madame Sarti.

02:18:13.251 --> 02:18:17.187
- Hello, Monique.
- Hello, Louise.

02:18:18.757 --> 02:18:21.590
So you are leading in points
for the championship, Nino.

02:18:22.059 --> 02:18:25.860
But not by as many points
as I would like, Madame Sarti.

02:18:26.197 --> 02:18:29.064
All you have to do
is to beat my husband.

02:18:29.734 --> 02:18:32.531
The question is,
is he ready to be beaten?

02:18:37.642 --> 02:18:41.806
Please excuse me,
I have some work to do back at the hotel.

02:18:42.180 --> 02:18:45.081
- Nino, tell Jean-Pierre...
- Yes, yes.

02:18:51.957 --> 02:18:55.255
- She's quite good-looking, isn't she?
- Yes.

02:18:55.860 --> 02:18:59.421
Of course, for one
who cares for the type.

02:19:00.699 --> 02:19:04.294
Yes. Excuse me,
Madame Sarti.

02:19:25.223 --> 02:19:28.590
Oh, no, wait.
Let me stand... It's better?

02:19:35.433 --> 02:19:39.893
The question is, Jean-Pierre,
what are you going to do about it?

02:19:40.071 --> 02:19:42.004
Do?
I don't understand.

02:19:42.540 --> 02:19:45.906
The time for losing comes
to every man, of course.

02:19:46.076 --> 02:19:49.171
I had not expected yours
to come so soon.

02:19:49.614 --> 02:19:51.514
There have been problems with the car.

02:19:51.683 --> 02:19:53.048
Come, come, Sarti.

02:19:53.218 --> 02:19:56.619
I expect excuses like that
from lesser men than you.

02:19:57.255 --> 02:19:59.780
You've been one of the best
that ever lived.

02:19:59.991 --> 02:20:02.687
There is no question of that
in my mind.

02:20:02.861 --> 02:20:07.958
Never a wrong move, the concentration
always there, 100 percent.

02:20:09.067 --> 02:20:11.058
Until this woman.

02:20:11.436 --> 02:20:14.405
You have been misled,
Signor Manetta.

02:20:14.572 --> 02:20:17.905
You take me for a trained dog
to jump at the snap of your fingers?

02:20:18.076 --> 02:20:20.044
My life belongs
to no one but myself.

02:20:20.211 --> 02:20:24.170
I've been thinking seriously
of your retirement, Sarti.

02:20:24.482 --> 02:20:25.779
Then retire me now.

02:20:28.453 --> 02:20:30.978
Kindly lower your voice.

02:20:31.189 --> 02:20:33.214
Of course I will not retire you now.

02:20:33.391 --> 02:20:35.154
Tomorrow there is a race to be run.

02:20:35.326 --> 02:20:38.955
And I also well know
that you want to drive it.

02:20:41.266 --> 02:20:44.929
But after tomorrow,
who knows, Jean-Pierre?

02:20:45.970 --> 02:20:50.771
After tomorrow, Signor Manetta,
I will decide to retire or not.

02:20:50.942 --> 02:20:54.673
Sarti, you are even further gone
than I thought.

02:20:55.380 --> 02:20:57.848
A pity.
A great pity.

02:20:58.550 --> 02:21:02.008
I always considered you
to be the best.

02:21:03.888 --> 02:21:05.412
I'm still the best.

02:21:18.336 --> 02:21:20.327
What brings you
to Monza, Monique?

02:21:21.606 --> 02:21:24.905
- Business, of course.
- Of course.

02:21:47.065 --> 02:21:49.226
Nino wonders if you're ready
to be beaten.

02:21:50.735 --> 02:21:52.862
No one is ever ready for that.

02:21:54.873 --> 02:21:57.740
You will never retire,
Jean-Pierre.

02:21:57.909 --> 02:22:00.434
What does it matter to you, Monique?

02:22:00.612 --> 02:22:01.636
- To me?
- Yeah.

02:22:03.214 --> 02:22:06.377
As always, as a hero,
you're a good asset to the company.

02:22:07.886 --> 02:22:12.186
Well, perhaps I'm tired
of being an asset for the company.

02:22:12.357 --> 02:22:16.794
And tired too, of this farce we perform,
you and I, for public consumption.

02:22:16.961 --> 02:22:21.455
But it doesn't really matter that you
are tired of these things, Jean-Pierre.

02:22:21.633 --> 02:22:27.230
If you should decide not to continue
with the... The farce, as you call it...

02:22:27.539 --> 02:22:29.598
that, of course, is entirely up to you.

02:22:31.009 --> 02:22:32.943
But it will make no difference.

02:22:33.111 --> 02:22:34.703
As long as you're my husband...

02:22:34.879 --> 02:22:38.406
the company will have the prestige
of your name and...

02:22:38.683 --> 02:22:43.245
whether or not, you ever step
into one of these again.

02:22:44.022 --> 02:22:47.014
And you will always be my husband.

02:22:47.525 --> 02:22:48.924
You know that, don't you?

02:22:52.430 --> 02:22:56.890
This one,
she may be different to you...

02:22:57.268 --> 02:22:59.429
but not to me.

02:22:59.871 --> 02:23:03.363
To me, she is just like all the others.

02:23:04.275 --> 02:23:07.108
And we will always be married,
you and I.

02:23:07.812 --> 02:23:09.302
Stay away from me, Monique.

02:23:09.480 --> 02:23:10.606
Let me alone, please.

02:23:16.087 --> 02:23:19.284
Tell me. What terrible thing
have I done to you...

02:23:19.457 --> 02:23:24.087
that makes you want to nail me
to this absurd life we have together?

02:23:25.296 --> 02:23:26.991
What terrible thing, Monique?

02:23:33.805 --> 02:23:36.365
Do you think it's been worth it, Pat?

02:23:36.541 --> 02:23:39.305
All the effort,
even if I win tomorrow?

02:23:39.510 --> 02:23:41.444
Worth it to you?

02:23:42.614 --> 02:23:45.048
Only you can know that, Scott.

02:23:45.817 --> 02:23:46.909
Yeah, I suppose so.

02:23:49.654 --> 02:23:52.817
Well, let's go and have a party.

02:23:52.991 --> 02:23:56.085
Scott, are you sure you want to go?

02:23:56.261 --> 02:23:58.195
Wouldn't you rather rest?

02:23:58.363 --> 02:24:01.958
After tomorrow, I shall be
a long time resting. Come on.

02:24:06.271 --> 02:24:08.068
Have I thanked you?

02:24:08.273 --> 02:24:09.331
For what?

02:24:11.576 --> 02:24:12.975
For being here.

02:24:22.287 --> 02:24:23.948
Thank you.

02:24:32.630 --> 02:24:33.824
Hey, <i>sayonara.</i>

02:24:33.998 --> 02:24:36.899
My goodness, Nino. I thought
they belonged to the Yamura boys.

02:24:37.068 --> 02:24:38.899
I have them on temporary loan.

02:24:39.070 --> 02:24:42.130
- Really? Two of them?
- They are very small.

02:24:42.307 --> 02:24:44.605
See you later, maybe.

02:25:46.237 --> 02:25:48.330
Can I buy you a drink?

02:25:49.540 --> 02:25:51.474
I don't drink.

02:25:58.950 --> 02:26:01.009
I don't smoke.

02:26:25.476 --> 02:26:27.171
The end?

02:26:29.213 --> 02:26:31.078
The end.

02:26:36.254 --> 02:26:39.917
I looked at the photographs last night.
Very good.

02:26:41.092 --> 02:26:42.457
Thank you.

02:26:42.627 --> 02:26:45.653
And what you wrote,
also very good.

02:26:51.436 --> 02:26:55.873
Well, your work may be finished,
but mine is not.

02:26:58.443 --> 02:27:00.308
It's time.

02:27:00.645 --> 02:27:02.579
I don't want to see the race, Jean-Pierre.

02:27:04.382 --> 02:27:05.781
Why not?

02:27:06.984 --> 02:27:09.282
Because I'm ashamed.

02:27:11.155 --> 02:27:13.123
Ashamed?

02:27:14.258 --> 02:27:15.350
Of what?

02:27:16.093 --> 02:27:18.926
Of what it's meant to be, I suppose.

02:27:19.096 --> 02:27:20.791
The racing.

02:27:21.299 --> 02:27:25.998
And now, knowing
what it means to you, the uncertainty.

02:27:26.170 --> 02:27:29.435
I don't want to watch anymore.
Ever.

02:27:34.846 --> 02:27:36.905
You're being very foolish, you know.

02:27:38.082 --> 02:27:39.640
Let me be foolish, then.

02:27:41.352 --> 02:27:45.288
I'm going to win today.
You don't want to miss that, do you?

02:27:45.823 --> 02:27:48.587
Please, Jean-Pierre.
I don't want to go.

02:27:57.201 --> 02:27:59.032
Well...

02:28:03.508 --> 02:28:05.669
to work, then.

02:28:10.915 --> 02:28:12.280
I love you, Jean-Pierre.

02:28:15.753 --> 02:28:16.777
And I you.

02:28:22.326 --> 02:28:27.294
We'll have to discuss the consequences
of those terrible words?

02:28:52.957 --> 02:28:55.118
Hey, where were you last night?

02:28:55.660 --> 02:28:58.288
- Where were you?
- Come here.

02:29:05.036 --> 02:29:08.938
Am I expected to account
for my whereabouts at every moment?

02:29:09.106 --> 02:29:11.939
- Am I?
- It is not the same thing.

02:29:12.109 --> 02:29:13.804
You are a woman.

02:29:14.712 --> 02:29:17.647
- I'm leaving you.
- Leaving? For how long?

02:29:17.949 --> 02:29:21.180
For always, you fool.
Forever.

02:29:27.224 --> 02:29:30.159
I met a boy, an American...

02:29:30.328 --> 02:29:33.923
who wants to go to the Greek islands
and dive for relics.

02:29:35.066 --> 02:29:38.524
In the first place,
diving is a great bore.

02:29:38.803 --> 02:29:41.704
How do you know?
Have you ever done it?

02:29:41.872 --> 02:29:44.739
Some things one can tell
without doing them...

02:29:44.909 --> 02:29:47.343
that they will be a great bore.

02:29:47.511 --> 02:29:50.344
Underwater is for fish, not people.

02:29:50.514 --> 02:29:53.574
In the second place,
they are not relics at all.

02:29:54.018 --> 02:29:56.953
I have on good authority
from a close friend...

02:29:57.254 --> 02:30:01.315
that these things are manufactured
and then dumped into the water...

02:30:01.492 --> 02:30:04.484
to be found by foolish
American boy tourists.

02:30:04.662 --> 02:30:07.062
And the girls who are foolish enough
to go with them.

02:30:07.598 --> 02:30:10.396
This is the most ridiculous thing
I ever heard.

02:30:10.568 --> 02:30:14.436
I have it on very good authority
from a close friend.

02:30:17.308 --> 02:30:19.071
Do you want me to stay?

02:30:19.410 --> 02:30:22.106
You are old enough
to make your own decisions.

02:30:23.981 --> 02:30:26.541
Then I'm going, all right?

02:30:27.251 --> 02:30:30.778
Yes, I definitely think you should go
to the Greek islands...

02:30:30.955 --> 02:30:33.549
with your American boyfriend.

02:30:33.724 --> 02:30:35.954
I think you should go to hell.

02:30:56.213 --> 02:30:57.680
You gonna be in the pits today?

02:31:09.560 --> 02:31:13.496
<i>The last time this combined circuit</i>
<i>was used was in 1961.</i>

02:31:13.864 --> 02:31:15.591
<i>There were objections</i>
<i>from drivers who thought...</i>

02:31:15.766 --> 02:31:18.867
<i>the light one-and-a-half liter</i>
<i>Formula 1 cars of that time...</i>

02:31:19.036 --> 02:31:21.630
<i>were not suitable for the strain</i>
<i>imposed by the banking.</i>

02:31:21.806 --> 02:31:24.707
<i>Bearing in mind, the suspension</i>
<i>had to be a compromise setting...</i>

02:31:24.875 --> 02:31:27.343
<i>to allow for effective cornering</i>
<i>on the road section as well.</i>

02:31:28.079 --> 02:31:30.476
<i>However the bigger cars</i>
<i>of the present formula...</i>

02:31:30.648 --> 02:31:33.811
<i>should be better able</i>
<i>to stand up to the conditions.</i>

02:31:37.254 --> 02:31:39.279
Hi, Pat.
How are you?

02:31:39.457 --> 02:31:43.325
- I'm okay. You?
- All right.

02:31:44.095 --> 02:31:46.495
Hope he beats you
by at least 10 laps today.

02:31:48.065 --> 02:31:49.999
I'm glad you feel that way.

02:31:50.234 --> 02:31:51.633
What if he doesn't?

02:31:52.269 --> 02:31:54.134
We'll survive it one way or another.

02:31:56.373 --> 02:31:57.567
Good luck.

02:32:45.856 --> 02:32:48.620
<i>Scott Stoddard has 27 points</i>
<i>in the championship...</i>

02:32:48.793 --> 02:32:50.693
<i>exactly the same as Jean-Pierre Sarti.</i>

02:32:50.861 --> 02:32:55.230
<i>In the lead with 28 points is Nino Barlini,</i>
<i>while Pete Aron has 26.</i>

02:32:55.733 --> 02:32:59.362
<i>In just two hours, one of these men</i>
<i>will be the new world champion.</i>

02:33:04.642 --> 02:33:05.836
<i>They're off.</i>

02:33:08.879 --> 02:33:10.312
<i>Sarti is stalled.</i>

02:33:10.481 --> 02:33:11.778
<i>He can't get away.</i>

02:33:13.417 --> 02:33:18.286
Go away! You will disqualify me!
No, no! No!

02:33:26.964 --> 02:33:28.727
<i>Sarti's away at last.</i>

02:33:29.066 --> 02:33:31.027
<i>And the leaders are onto the banking</i>
<i>for the first time...</i>

02:33:31.202 --> 02:33:34.565
<i>with Barlini's Ferrari in front</i>
<i>of Stoddard's BRM and Aron's Yamura.</i>

02:33:34.738 --> 02:33:36.535
<i>Then Brabham, Gurney and Scarfiotti.</i>

02:33:36.707 --> 02:33:41.371
<i>The order's Barlini, Stoddard,</i>
<i>Aron, Brabham, Gurney, Scarfiotti.</i>

02:34:15.846 --> 02:34:17.143
<i>And tell me, Scott...</i>

02:34:17.314 --> 02:34:21.478
<i>are there any particular problems</i>
<i>in driving on the Monza banking?</i>

02:34:22.019 --> 02:34:23.782
<i>The banking?</i>

02:34:24.088 --> 02:34:27.854
<i>It's just so damn rough up there,</i>
<i>and that the car flicks all over the place.</i>

02:34:28.025 --> 02:34:29.925
<i>We're never below 180, you know.</i>

02:34:30.094 --> 02:34:32.460
<i>At that speed, your reactions</i>
<i>can barely keep up...</i>

02:34:32.630 --> 02:34:34.791
<i>with these sudden changes in direction.</i>

02:34:34.965 --> 02:34:38.560
<i>The trouble is, the high centrifugal forces</i>
<i>push the car into the banking...</i>

02:34:38.736 --> 02:34:40.795
<i>and use up</i>
<i>all the suspension movement.</i>

02:34:40.971 --> 02:34:43.997
<i>So, what you're driving</i>
<i>becomes a car with no springs.</i>

02:34:44.174 --> 02:34:47.166
<i>It feels like you're getting a series</i>
<i>of punches in the back.</i>

02:34:47.344 --> 02:34:49.175
<i>I hate it. I'm sick of pain.</i>

02:34:49.446 --> 02:34:52.347
<i>But it's what the car is suffering</i>
<i>that really worries me.</i>

02:34:52.516 --> 02:34:54.347
<i>Because no matter how the car</i>
<i>is set up...</i>

02:34:54.518 --> 02:34:56.645
<i>it bottoms at several places</i>
<i>on both bankings.</i>

02:34:56.820 --> 02:35:00.085
<i>The underside of the car just comes</i>
<i>crashing down onto the biggest bumps.</i>

02:35:00.257 --> 02:35:02.851
<i>Everything's shaking</i>
<i>and banging all the time.</i>

02:35:03.027 --> 02:35:06.155
<i>Sometimes you could swear</i>
<i>the whole thing's falling to bits.</i>

02:35:49.673 --> 02:35:51.334
<i>On none of us</i>
<i>like Monza very much.</i>

02:35:51.508 --> 02:35:54.443
<i>It's so damn fast</i>
<i>and they run so close together...</i>

02:35:54.611 --> 02:36:00.277
<i>it requires fantastic concentration</i>
<i>and rather special skills.</i>

02:36:00.451 --> 02:36:02.112
<i>It's slipstreaming, for instance.</i>

02:36:02.286 --> 02:36:07.883
<i>At speeds reaching 180 miles an hour,</i>
<i>race car's making a big hole in the air.</i>

02:36:08.058 --> 02:36:13.155
<i>As the car goes through, the air rushes back</i>
<i>into the hole and creates a hell of a draft.</i>

02:36:13.330 --> 02:36:16.458
<i>And that draft's strong enough to pull</i>
<i>a following car along at...</i>

02:36:16.633 --> 02:36:19.796
<i>Oh, 10 miles</i>
<i>more than his usual top speed.</i>

02:36:20.304 --> 02:36:23.364
<i>If yours is the last car in a bunch,</i>
<i>you can get a terrific tow.</i>

02:36:23.540 --> 02:36:26.941
<i>You can back way off the gas pedal</i>
<i>and maintain the same speed.</i>

02:36:27.378 --> 02:36:28.902
<i>Then you can put your foot down...</i>

02:36:29.079 --> 02:36:33.880
<i>pull out of the slipstream and maybe</i>
<i>overtake two, three cars at once.</i>

02:36:34.051 --> 02:36:37.509
<i>The only thing to do here is to drive</i>
<i>just as fast as you know how...</i>

02:36:37.688 --> 02:36:39.349
<i>and hope your car doesn't break.</i>

02:38:27.564 --> 02:38:30.562
<i>At the end of the fifth lap,</i>
<i>Barlini's in the lead by five seconds.</i>

02:38:31.168 --> 02:38:34.103
<i>Now both Stoddard and Aron</i>
<i>have lost the Ferrari's slipstream.</i>

02:38:34.271 --> 02:38:37.069
<i>And they're dropping back</i>
<i>in their great dice for second place.</i>

02:39:03.233 --> 02:39:08.170
<i>And coming up the main straight now is number four,</i>
<i>Jean-Pierre Sarti's Ferrari in 14th place.</i>

02:39:08.338 --> 02:39:11.307
<i>With 10 laps gone</i>
<i>and only 18 seconds behind Barlini...</i>

02:39:11.475 --> 02:39:14.774
<i>after losing nearly half a minute</i>
<i>when his engine stalled at the start.</i>

02:39:14.945 --> 02:39:18.608
<i>With 40 laps to go, Sarti could still</i>
<i>catch the leader and win the race.</i>

02:40:04.861 --> 02:40:07.329
Are you never afraid?

02:40:08.031 --> 02:40:09.658
Not ever.

02:40:09.833 --> 02:40:11.391
Why?

02:40:12.569 --> 02:40:17.370
Because I am immortal.

02:40:26.049 --> 02:40:29.314
Why do you drive racing cars?

02:40:29.953 --> 02:40:32.786
Or do you not think about it?

02:40:33.056 --> 02:40:36.992
Well, Mr. Yamura,
I don't think there's one of us...

02:40:37.160 --> 02:40:40.755
who doesn't ask himself
at least once in the middle of a race:

02:40:40.931 --> 02:40:43.399
"What the hell am I doing here?"

02:40:43.667 --> 02:40:49.333
Of course, when it's over, we conveniently
forget that we ask ourselves that question.

02:40:50.274 --> 02:40:52.538
I think about it.

02:40:52.776 --> 02:40:55.267
There are a lot of reasons, I don't know.

02:40:55.445 --> 02:40:58.812
Maybe to do something...

02:40:58.982 --> 02:41:04.215
that brings you so close to
the possibility of death and to survive it...

02:41:04.388 --> 02:41:08.518
is to feel life and living
so much more intensely.

02:41:19.536 --> 02:41:22.767
- Be careful there, it's slippery.
- Okay.

02:41:25.042 --> 02:41:27.340
Can you manage all right?

02:41:31.581 --> 02:41:33.845
I'm all right. It's okay.

02:41:36.420 --> 02:41:38.081
I'll get Thompson to bring lunch up.

02:41:38.255 --> 02:41:40.815
- I'll eat downstairs, Mom.
- You can't go downstairs again.

02:41:40.991 --> 02:41:43.983
Look, I'm getting up the stairs,
I can certainly get down them.

02:41:46.196 --> 02:41:49.427
If worse comes to the worse, I can
always slide down the banisters.

02:41:49.599 --> 02:41:52.159
- Right?
- Yes.

02:42:30.941 --> 02:42:33.034
This isn't good,
you know, what I feel now.

02:42:33.210 --> 02:42:34.507
What do you feel?

02:42:34.678 --> 02:42:38.046
That I would almost rather stay
here with you than get into the car.

02:42:38.215 --> 02:42:40.512
Ah, almost.

02:42:40.817 --> 02:42:45.481
I suppose at my age, one moves
slowly from one habit to the next.

02:42:45.856 --> 02:42:46.845
I must go, darling.

02:43:35.639 --> 02:43:37.607
<i>There's Barlini on his 17th lap.</i>

02:43:37.774 --> 02:43:41.039
<i>His Ferrari is just a bit too fast,</i>
<i>even for Pete Aron's Yamura...</i>

02:43:41.211 --> 02:43:42.644
<i>and Scott Stoddard's BRM.</i>

02:43:42.813 --> 02:43:44.474
<i>They're in second and third places.</i>

02:43:44.648 --> 02:43:48.709
<i>There's a splendid scrap for fourth place,</i>
<i>with Tim Randolph in the second Yamura...</i>

02:43:48.885 --> 02:43:52.753
<i>just ahead of Dan Gurney in the Eagle,</i>
<i>and Bob Turner in the other BRM.</i>

02:44:20.484 --> 02:44:22.042
<i>As they sweep around the banking this time...</i>

02:44:22.219 --> 02:44:25.416
<i>Sarti's gonna catch up with the three cars</i>
<i>fighting for fourth place.</i>

02:44:25.589 --> 02:44:29.457
<i>He's passed Tim Randolph from the Japanese Yamura,</i>
<i>now watch him go underneath Gurney in the Eagle.</i>

02:44:29.626 --> 02:44:32.527
<i>Yes, he's passed him, and now</i>
<i>he's passing Bob Turner in the BRM.</i>

02:44:32.696 --> 02:44:33.924
<i>He's fourth. Sarti's fourth.</i>

02:44:34.564 --> 02:44:37.124
<i>There are three slow cars just in front.</i>
<i>When Sarti's lapped them...</i>

02:44:37.300 --> 02:44:40.963
<i>he'll only have Aron and Stoddard</i>
<i>between him and the leader, Barlini.</i>

02:45:57.581 --> 02:45:59.811
<i>We've just heard</i>
<i>there's been an accident.</i>

02:46:01.651 --> 02:46:05.553
<i>It's Sarti. Sarti's Ferrari</i>
<i>has gone clean over the north banking...</i>

02:46:05.722 --> 02:46:08.885
<i>and landed at the side</i>
<i>of the track below. Then it caught fire.</i>

02:46:26.743 --> 02:46:28.540
Oh, Jean-Pierre!

02:46:31.181 --> 02:46:32.705
Oh, Jean-Pierre.

02:46:32.882 --> 02:46:35.510
Jean-Pierre. Oh, Jean-Pierre.

02:46:35.885 --> 02:46:37.648
Oh, Jean-Pierre.

02:46:37.821 --> 02:46:42.121
No. No!
No, Jean-Pierre!

02:46:43.326 --> 02:46:45.624
Jean-Pierre. Jean-Pierre!

02:46:45.996 --> 02:46:49.432
No! Jean-Pierre!

02:46:50.867 --> 02:46:54.860
Jean-Pierre.
Jean-Pierre! Jean-Pierre.

02:46:58.108 --> 02:46:59.132
Jean-Pierre.

02:47:03.947 --> 02:47:06.211
Jean-Pierre!

02:47:06.483 --> 02:47:08.644
What do you want?
Is this what you want?

02:47:08.952 --> 02:47:13.582
Is this what you want?
Is this what you want?

02:47:47.891 --> 02:47:50.724
<i>The Commendatore <i>is showing</i>
<i>a black flag to his drivers.</i></i>

02:47:50.894 --> 02:47:53.328
<i>He's withdrawing the whole Ferrari team.</i>

02:47:53.496 --> 02:47:55.930
<i>I don't think it's been done like this</i>
<i>for about 40 years.</i>

02:47:56.099 --> 02:47:59.034
<i>The Alfa Romeo team manager</i>
<i>did the same thing once in the '20s...</i>

02:47:59.202 --> 02:48:02.603
<i>when Antonio Ascari was killed</i>
<i>in the French Grand Prix.</i>

02:48:02.772 --> 02:48:06.503
<i>He showed the black flag to Campari and</i>
<i>Brilli-Peri when the Alfas were in the lead.</i>

02:48:19.055 --> 02:48:23.287
<i>Here comes Barlini into the pits now</i>
<i>in response to the black-flag signal.</i>

02:48:23.460 --> 02:48:25.792
- Jean-Pierre?
<i>- He'll have to be told the terrible news...</i>

02:48:25.962 --> 02:48:27.361
<i>of his team leader's death.</i>

02:48:27.931 --> 02:48:31.765
<i>And this tragic race is over</i>
<i>for the young Sicilian.</i>

02:48:32.101 --> 02:48:33.625
<i>In the lead are Aron and Stoddard.</i>

02:48:33.703 --> 02:48:37.139
<i>They've just gone past the pits,</i>
<i>side by side, fighting for the lead.</i>

02:49:01.698 --> 02:49:03.632
<i>Last lap now.</i>
<i>Stoddard or Aron?</i>

02:49:03.800 --> 02:49:06.496
<i>They're still neck and neck,</i>
<i>wheel to wheel, the whole way.</i>

02:49:50.613 --> 02:49:52.513
<i>Stoddard's in front as they</i>
<i>come into the last corner.</i>

02:49:52.782 --> 02:49:54.613
<i>Aron, in the Yamura,</i>
<i>is right on his tail.</i>

02:49:54.784 --> 02:49:56.945
<i>He can still beat the BRM to the flag.</i>

02:50:17.841 --> 02:50:21.272
